    <h2>Course Name: Cancer Biology</h2>
    <h3> Course Description:</h3>
    <p> Cancer is one of the leading causes of death worldwide. Understanding the biology of cancer is crucial to 
    develop new therapies and treatments to fight this disease. This course will cover the fundamentals of cancer biology, 
    including the mechanisms underlying cancer initiation, progression, and metastasis.
    The course will start with a brief overview of normal cell biology and how it is perturbed in cancer cells. 
    We will discuss the molecular basis of cancer, including genetic mutations and alterations in signal transduction pathways. 
    Students will learn about the different types of cancers, their clinical presentation, and the current therapeutic options 
    available.
    We will also cover the role of the tumor microenvironment in promoting cancer progression and how cancer 
    cells interact with their surroundings. The course will delve into the complex mechanisms of cancer metastasis, 
    including the biology of cancer stem cells, the epithelial-mesenchymal transition, and the importance of the immune system 
    in cancer surveillance.</p>
    <h3> Year Group:</h3>
    <p> This course is meant for First Year Students</p>
