    <h2>Course Name: Neuro-Oncology: Understanding Brain Tumors and Treatment Options</h2>
    <h3> Course Description</h3>
    <p> This course provides a comprehensive overview of the field of neuro-oncology, including the biology of brain tumors, 
        the clinical presentation of brain tumors, and the various treatment options available for patients. Students will 
        learn about the different types of brain tumors, their molecular basis, and how they are classified. The course will cover 
        the clinical manifestations of brain tumors, including neurological symptoms, cognitive deficits, and quality of life issues.
        In addition to learning about the biology and clinical presentation of brain tumors, students will explore the different 
        treatment options available for patients with brain tumors. This will include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, 
        targeted therapy, and immunotherapy. The course will delve into the potential benefits and risks associated with each 
        treatment modality and how they are used in various contexts, such as primary and metastatic brain tumors.
        Throughout the course, students will engage with real-world cases and cutting-edge research, giving them a deeper 
        understanding of the challenges faced by neuro-oncologists and the latest advances in the field. Students will also 
        learn about the multidisciplinary approach to patient care in neuro-oncology, including the role of neurosurgeons, 
        medical oncologists, radiation oncologists, and supportive care providers.</p>
